That's what I was thinking when I set out to raise the truck back to stock.
Whoever lowered the front end must have decided to remove some leaves rather
than buy a drop kit. It had to be that way because the arms are right at the
stop and I have no spring. The only thing that even holds my trailing arms
off the stops is my gas shocks, and now my coil over shocks installed last
night. (Man, I can't believe how easy front shocks are on this thing to
install). If they had used drop spindles or drop arms I would still have
full spring in the torsion bars.

My rear end was just a matter of pulling the spring plates and torsion bars
and adjusting the spring plates on them back to factory 20 degrees from
frame level. I built my own spring plate compression tool and degree plate
from pictures out of the manual. Worked so slick I thought I could go into
the rear end raising back to stock business!

67 Single Cab
71 Trike
VolksAir
Ray, Kent WA
